<strong>The lecture notes are a collaborative effort of the participants in the course. You are not required to contribute to the lecture notes, but are encouraged to do so. Together, we can create resources that will be helpful to everyone.</strong></p>
<h2> <span class="mw-headline" id="Notes_for_Week_3:_5.1._Price_Ceilings">Notes for Week 3: 5.1. Price Ceilings</span></h2>
<p><a href="/wiki/images/5/5b/5.1_Price_Ceilings.jpg" class="image"><img alt="5.1 Price Ceilings.jpg" src="/wiki/images/5/5b/5.1_Price_Ceilings.jpg" width="1366" height="768" /></a></p>
<p>•   Example: market for apartments: </p>
<p>o   The equilibrium price for a 1-room apartment is $600</p>
<p>o   The government sets a ceiling of $400</p>
<p>o   The number of renters raises ($$Q&#95;2$$), while the number of landlords declines ($$Q&#95;3$$)</p>
<p>o   The result of this policy is that a smaller number of apartments would be rented ($$Q&#95;3 &lt; Q&#95;1$$)</p>
<p>o   The case is similar to the tomatoes shortage: there are people standing in line (8 – 4 = 4), therefore prices should increase</p>
<p>o   Market cannot work this way if prices are not allowed to increase for a government policy</p>
<p>o   Landlords can therefore charge larger prices for utilities (it’s a legal way to increase the price), decrease the quality of the apartments, or rent them on the black market</p>
<p></p>

